id: pm-2c28
title: "ADR: pm extensions & SDK packages must be authored fully in TypeScript"
description: "Policy ADR: every pm extension and SDK package MUST be authored fully in TypeScript (TS source compiled to a JS entry the loader imports), never plain JavaScript, to guarantee full type safety and contract/spec enforcement at author time. Aligns the pm extension/package init scaffolder with the first-party packages (index.ts compiled to index.js) and reframes the SDK authoring docs/docstrings TypeScript-first."
type: Decision
status: open
priority: 1
tags[4]: adr,"area:extensions","area:sdk",authoring
created_at: "2026-06-23T20:34:53.658Z"
updated_at: "2026-06-23T20:36:18.504Z"
assignee: claude-code-agent
author: claude-code-agent
parent: pm-m2u1
dependencies[2]{id,kind,created_at,author,source_kind}:
  pm-09rh,related,"2026-06-23T20:36:18.487Z",null,null
  pm-2p38,related,"2026-06-23T20:36:18.487Z",null,null
body: "## Context\n\nThe SDK authoring surface (`define*` builders, `composeExtension`, the modular-authoring primitives) and the `pm extension/package init` scaffolder were historically framed around **plain JavaScript** packages ŌĆö the scaffolder emits `index.js` with a single JSDoc `@param {import(\"...\").ExtensionApi}` annotation, and the SDK docs/docstrings justify the `define*` helpers with \"plain-JavaScript packages cannot write TS annotations.\"\n\nThis is inconsistent with reality: every first-party package (`packages/pm-*`) is authored in **TypeScript** ŌĆö `index.ts` source importing SDK types from `src/sdk/index.js`, compiled to `index.js` (the manifest `entry`) via `tsconfig.packages.json`. A plain-JS authoring path forfeits the very thing the SDK exists to provide: end-to-end type safety and compile-time enforcement of the registration contracts/specifications.\n\n## Decision\n\nEvery pm extension and SDK package MUST be authored **fully in TypeScript**, never plain JavaScript:\n\n1. Source is `index.ts` (and any siblings) written in TypeScript, importing types from `@unbrained/pm-cli/sdk`.\n2. The TypeScript is compiled to a JavaScript entry (`./index.js`) that the manifest `entry` points to and the loader imports ŌĆö the loader continues to import compiled JS; TypeScript is the authoring layer, not a runtime loader feature.\n3. `pm extension init` / `pm package init` scaffold TypeScript source + a `tsconfig.json` + a `build` script, mirroring the first-party packages.\n4. All SDK docs (`docs/SDK.md`, `docs/EXTENSIONS.md`), docstrings, and examples are reframed TypeScript-first. The `define*` / `defineExtensionBlueprint` identity helpers are justified by their TypeScript value ŌĆö preserving narrow literal types while checking against the interface, contextual handler-parameter inference, colocated/exported/unit-testable definitions (the Vite `defineConfig` pattern) ŌĆö not by \"JS can't annotate.\"\n\n## Rationale\n\n- Full type safety is the SDK's core value proposition; TypeScript enforces the registration contracts (`CommandDefinition`, `ExtensionManifest`, capability sets) at author time instead of deferring failures to `api.register*`/load time.\n- The first-party packages already prove the `index.ts` ŌåÆ compiled `index.js` pattern; standardizing the scaffolder on it removes the JS/TS split-brain and gives external authors a path identical to the maintainers'.\n- Identity helpers (`define*`) remain valuable in TypeScript: they are the idiomatic way to get literal-type preservation + inference without losing the interface check, and to make definitions exportable/unit-testable apart from `activate`.\n\n## Alternatives considered\n\n- **Keep the JS-first scaffold, document TS as optional.** Rejected: undermines the type-safety guarantee and perpetuates the split-brain with first-party packages.\n- **Load TypeScript directly at runtime (tsx/transpile-on-load).** Rejected: adds a runtime transpile dependency and startup cost; compiled JS entry is simpler, faster, and matches the existing loader.\n\n## Consequences\n\n- `pm extension/package init` scaffolds `index.ts` + `tsconfig.json` + `build` script; the manifest `entry` stays `./index.js` (compiled output); the README documents `npm install && npm run build` before load.\n- Scaffold tests, smoke (`smoke:external-packages`), and dogfood (`dogfood:package-first`) flows must build the TypeScript scaffold before loading.\n- SDK docs and docstrings are reframed TypeScript-first; the legacy \"plain-JS authors\" framing is removed as files are touched.\n- Tracked by the TypeScript-first scaffolding feature and the modular declarative-authoring feature (pm-2p38)."
